{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"479398d4-702b-4452-a515-057f018ebea6","content":"Here's the recommended approach using `dotnet-trace` with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the container:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process ID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a CPU trace (30 seconds example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**To get the file out of the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- Use `--format speedscope` if you want browser-based analysis without Windows tools.\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use **dotnet-monitor** as a sidecar instead — it exposes a `/trace` HTTP endpoint.\n- For a lower-level alternative, `perf record` works too but requires `SYS_ADMIN` / `privileged` and is harder to symbolize.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"958b9cd8-4822-4957-910d-51bd52549fca","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":386,"requestId":"2C45:9B616:165162B:1901A39:69F94719"},"id":"7953912c-b1ba-451c-a82a-cec075ec09d2","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:25:54.914Z","parentId":"1873517a-1b11-4979-98cb-954165f0dcb6"}
